### PHP Form Validation

Form validation ensures user input meets required criteria before processing.

### Client-side vs Server-side

| Type | Pros | Cons |
|------|------|------|
| Client-side (JavaScript) | Immediate feedback | Can be bypassed |
| Server-side (PHP) | Secure, reliable | Requires page reload |

> Always validate on the server side even if you validate on the client side.

### Basic Validation Functions

| Function | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `empty()` | Check if variable is empty |
| `isset()` | Check if variable is set |
| `trim()` | Remove whitespace from both ends |
| `strip_tags()` | Strip HTML tags |
| `htmlspecialchars()` | Escape HTML entities |
| `filter_var()` | Filter with built-in validation |

### Example

```php
<?php
$name = $email = $website = "";
$nameErr = $emailErr = $websiteErr = "";

if ($_SERVER["REQUEST_METHOD"] == "POST") {
    if (empty($_POST["name"])) {
        $nameErr = "Name is required";
    } else {
        $name = htmlspecialchars(trim($_POST["name"]));
    }

    if (empty($_POST["email"])) {
        $emailErr = "Email is required";
    } else {
        $email = filter_var(trim($_POST["email"]), FILTER_VALIDATE_EMAIL);
        if ($email === false) {
            $emailErr = "Invalid email format";
        }
    }
}
?>
```

> **Key Point:** Use `filter_var()` with validation filters like `FILTER_VALIDATE_EMAIL`, `FILTER_VALIDATE_URL`, and `FILTER_VALIDATE_INT` for reliable input validation.
